data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

**What happened:** In C# 14, new implicit conversions from arrays to `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` mean that `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. The `MemoryExtensions` method **cannot be represented in an expression tree**, so it throws at runtime when the expression is compiled/interpreted.

**How to fix:** Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<T>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);
```

All three prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the call within the expression tree–compatible `System.Linq.Enumerable` API.
